   },
   "source": [
    "# 🟤 Chapter 6: Algorithm Chains and Pipelines\n",
    "**Reference:** *Introduction to Machine Learning with Python: A Guide for Data Scientists* by Andreas C. Müller & Sarah Guido\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## 6.1 The Danger of Data Leakage\n",
    "Most machine learning applications require a multi-stage sequence of preprocessing operations (such as data scaling via `MinMaxScaler` or feature extraction via `PCA`) before passing the data matrix into a supervised estimator.\n",
    "\n",
    "A common mistake when combining preprocessing with cross-validation is applying the transformations to the entire dataset *before* running `cross_val_score`. If you call `.fit_transform()` on your global data array, the scaler incorporates structural information (such as the maximum and minimum values) from your validation and test sets into its calculations. \n",
    "\n",
    "This phenomenon is known as **Data Leakage** (or information leakage). During cross-validation, the model evaluates data that has already passed information to the scaler, resulting in an artificially inflated validation score. When the model is later deployed to predict on true, unseen real-world observations, its performance will deteriorate significantly because it no longer has access to this leaked information."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {
    "id": "33UjSRqZfQGE"
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "from sklearn.datasets import load_breast_cancer\n",
    "from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split\n",
    "\n",
    "# Set runtime environment configurations\n",
    "%matplotlib inline\n",
    "plt.style.use('seaborn-v0_8-whitegrid')\n",
    "print(\"Pipeline processing toolkit successfully loaded.\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "m5kLLtEMfQGE"
   },
   "source": [
    "## 6.2 Constructing Pipelines\n",
    "To solve the problem of data leakage, Scikit-learn provides the `Pipeline` class. A pipeline encapsulates multiple transformer steps alongside a final estimator into a single, unified Scikit-learn estimator interface.\n",
    "\n",
    "When you wrap your workflow in a pipeline, the preprocessing operations are strictly constrained. The transformer stages are only trained (`.fit()`) on the **training folds of the cross-validation partition** during each loop iteration. The validation folds are kept completely separate and are only transformed (`.transform()`) using the scaling weights learned from the training data. This ensures a clean separation between training and validation data, preventing information from leaking across validation folds."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {
    "id": "pp2v_qVCfQGF"
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline\n",
    "from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler\n",
    "from sklearn.svm import SVC\n",
    "\n",
    "# Load the real-world Breast Cancer dataset for classification\n",
    "cancer = load_breast_cancer()\n",
    "X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(cancer.data, cancer.target, random_state=0)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Define the algorithmic chain inside the Pipeline object\n",
    "# Steps are provided as a list of tuples: (name_string, estimator_instance)\n",
    "pipe = Pipeline([(\"scaler\", MinMaxScaler()), (\"svm\", SVC())])\n",
    "\n",
    "# The pipeline can be treated exactly like a standard Scikit-learn model\n",
    "# calling .fit() fits the scaler and then trains the SVM on the scaled data\n",
    "pipe.fit(X_train, y_train)\n",
    "test_accuracy = pipe.score(X_test, y_test)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Test Set Evaluation Accuracy using Pipeline: {test_accuracy:.3f}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "8zDCQQswfQGF"
   },
   "source": [
    "## 6.3 Integrating Pipelines with Grid Search\n",
    "The true power of the `Pipeline` class becomes evident when it is integrated with hyperparameter tuning via `GridSearchCV`. By tuning your hyperparameters through a pipeline interface, you ensure that your preprocessing scaling weights are recalculated independently for each data split during cross-validation.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Syntax Requirements for Pipeline Grids\n",
    "When defining a parameter grid for `GridSearchCV` to use within a pipeline, you must specify which step a parameter belongs to. This is done using the syntax: `[step_name]__[parameter_name]`. Notice the required **double underscore (`__`)** connecting the step name to its hyperparameter key."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {
    "id": "D714z_eCfQGF"
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV\n",
    "\n",
    "# Define the hyperparameter grid using the pipeline step names as prefixes\n",
    "param_grid = {\n",
    "    'svm__C': [0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 10, 100],\n",
    "    'svm__gamma': [0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 10, 100]\n",
    "}\n",
    "\n",
    "# Pass the pipeline instance into the GridSearchCV object\n",
    "grid = GridSearchCV(pipe, param_grid=param_grid, cv=5)\n",
    "grid.fit(X_train, y_train)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Optimal Parameters found within the Pipeline:\")\n",
    "print(grid.best_params_)\n",
    "print(f\"\\nBest Cross-Validation Score: {grid.best_score_:.3f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Final Generalization Test Score:  {grid.score(X_test, y_test):.3f}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "Hpq7rzIMfQGG"
   },
   "source": [
    "## 6.4 Visualizing Pipeline Execution vs. Traditional Workflows\n",
    "To better understand why data leakage occurs, let's look at a visual representation of how data flows through a traditional machine learning workflow versus a secure pipeline architecture."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {
    "id": "owyLzB2SfQGG"
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    ""

    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(14, 5))\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot 1: Traditional Preprocessing Workflow (Prone to Data Leakage)\n",
    "axes[0].add_patch(plt.Rectangle((0.1, 0.5), 0.8, 0.4, color='red', alpha=0.25))\n",
    "axes[0].text(0.5, 0.7, 'Global Data Transformations\\n(Scaler fits entire dataset simultaneously)', ha='center', va='center', fontsize=12, weight='bold')\n",
    "axes[0].add_patch(plt.Rectangle((0.1, 0.1), 0.8, 0.3, color='blue', alpha=0.25))\n",
    "axes[0].text(0.5, 0.25, 'Cross-Validation Loops\\n(Validation splits are already contaminated\\nby global information leakage)', ha='center', va='center', fontsize=11)\n",
    "axes[0].set_title(\"Traditional Workflow (Suffers from Data Leakage)\", fontsize=14, color='darkred')\n",
    "axes[0].axis('off')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot 2: Secure Pipeline Workflow (Protected and Isolated)\n",
    "axes[1].add_patch(plt.Rectangle((0.1, 0.1), 0.8, 0.8, color='green', alpha=0.25))\n",
    "axes[1].text(0.5, 0.78, 'Cross-Validation Fold Splits', ha='center', va='center', fontsize=12, weight='bold')\n",
    "axes[1].add_patch(plt.Rectangle((0.2, 0.42), 0.6, 0.2, color='orange', alpha=0.5))\n",
    "axes[1].text(0.5, 0.52, 'Isolated Preprocessing\\n(Scaler fits ONLY the active training fold)', ha='center', va='center', fontsize=11)\n",
    "axes[1].add_patch(plt.Rectangle((0.2, 0.16), 0.6, 0.2, color='blue', alpha=0.5))\n",
    "axes[1].text(0.5, 0.26, 'Model Fitting and Evaluation\\n(Validation fold data is completely secure)', ha='center', va='center', fontsize=11)\n",
    "axes[1].set_title(\"Pipeline Workflow (Protected against Data Leakage)\", fontsize=14, color='darkgreen')\n",
    "axes[1].axis('off')\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 6.5 Chapter Summary\n",
    "Key takeaways from Chapter 6:\n",
    "- **Data Leakage** occurs when information from outside the training dataset is inadvertently used to train a model. This commonly happens when preprocessing steps are fit on the entire dataset prior to cross-validation.\n",
    "- The **Scikit-learn `Pipeline` class** addresses this problem by chaining preprocessing steps together with an estimator, ensuring that transformations are fit *only* on the active training folds during cross-validation.\n",
    "- Combining pipelines with **`GridSearchCV`** lets you evaluate different combinations of preprocessing settings and model hyperparameters simultaneously without compromising your cross-validation results."
   ]
  }
